The variation trend of the effective diffusivity (De
                           ) against the ultrasonic frequency is plotted in Fig. 2

                           [8], which shows that the moisture diffusivity in the silica gel De
                            tends to decrease with the increase of the acoustic frequency, especially under the higher power of ultrasound. This is because the acoustic energy decays more quickly under the higher frequency during its propagation, which indicates that the ultrasound with a higher frequency will result in a less uniform energy distribution in medium, and hence, achieve a lower utilization efficiency of acoustic energy in promoting the moisture diffusivity [12]. The higher power of ultrasound will surely result in the higher moisture diffusivity (De
                           ), and this can be reflected as well from Fig. 2.
